  <span id="freeText6775267135559962788" style="display:none">I read the original novella of Nightfall when I was in high school and loved it. The tenants of Asimov's hard and fantastical science fiction always amazed me and I rank it up with Clark's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/149075.The_Nine_Billion_Names_of_God" title="The Nine Billion Names of God by Arthur C. Clarke" rel="nofollow noopener">The Nine Billion Names of God</a> and Foster's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35136.Sentenced_to_Prism__Humanx_Commonwealth___12_" title="Sentenced to Prism (Humanx Commonwealth, #12) by Alan Dean Foster" rel="nofollow noopener">Sentenced to Prism</a> as some of my favorites. <br /><br />The planet Lagash has not experienced a true night in more than 2000 years and as the suns begin to set and darkness spreads across the land, people are driven mad by not only the lack of light but the fact that they themselves may not be alone in the universe. <br /><br />To me, the original story stands high above and beyond the rest of the "prequel" and "sequel" that Robert Silverberg added to the book in 1990, so I can give 3 stars to the beginning and end tales and 4 stars to the original. </span>
