  <span id="freeText3397082220759200986" style="display:none">This book is a tragedy. A fascinating concept ruined by regressive gender politics and an inexplicable twist ending that <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[religious totalitarianism is good, actually  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. In the world of Kalagash, darkness is only found in caves and other unnatural structures. Surrounded by no fewer than six suns, it is constantly bathed in light. But once every 2500 years or so, an eclipse plunges the whole planet into darkness. The population, unadapted to the "unnatural" night, goes mad and society crumbles. This fascinating premise is ruined by the single female character being a collection of "ice queen" professional woman who only loves her job until she meets the right guy tropes in a trench coat, and her emotions being portrayed as fickle and incomprehensible. <br /><br />If that wasn't bad enough, at the end of the book the religious authoritarian cult that has been the villains for the first 95% of the book <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[do an abrupt 180 to become the heroes after the main character realizes that in dire situations like the end of the world, religious totalitarianism is the only government that the drooling masses will accept. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Additionally, it's a very reductive imagination of the apocalypse, imagining a world where might makes right, and relying on gendered violence for cheap thrills. There's better dystopian fiction out there, and unfortunately even the intriguing and unique premise can't save this book from itself.</span>
